Governor Babajide Sanwo-Olu of Lagos State yesterday honoured no fewer than 1,000 public servants who have conscientiously spent over 30 years in active service of the state, saying his administration remain committed to the payment of 30,000 minimum wages. Among those honoured by Sanwo-Olu were 17 serving permanent secretaries who have spent between 30-34 years in the service, the Clerk of the Lagos State House of Assembly and other categories of workers who have dedicated over three decades of their life in the state public service. Speaking at the 2019 Long Service Merit Award held at the Lagos State Secretariat, Alausa, Sanwo-Olu, who was represented by the Secretary to the State Government, Mrs. Folahade Jaji, said his administration is committed to the payment of N30, 000 new minimum wage, urging workers in the state to key into his T.H.E.M.E.S agenda to take the state to a greater height. The state’s Head of Service, Mr. Hakeem Muri- Okunola, who was also at the event, explained that the award would further encourage diligence, commitment and loyalty among public servants in the state in anticipation that the award will spur them to continue to put in their best in the service of the state, adding that the award was a mark of honour to distinguished them among the state workforce. He said: “I congratulate and rejoice with the 1,000 proud recipients of today’s awards and their relations here present not only for the grace of God, which saw them through the last 30 years in the service of our dear state, in good health, but also for their dedication, diligence, loyalty and invaluable contributions to the public service.